Now in Lucretius imperium impero or imperito occurs six times, and the mss. always spell with m, and so Lucretius spelt I have no doubt: indeed many of these common words the silver age Ι believe more frequently wrote with η, than did that of Cicero. Then Virgil uses im- perium 40 times 3 and Ribbeck's capital mss. have m in every instance, except M which twice has inp, though one of these two cases is at least doubtful: for Aen. vm 381 Fogginius prints imperiis. Yet in defiance of all this evidence Wagner gives us inperium, surely without reason on any view of the case 3 for the foundation on which we must build is thus withdrawn from under our feet. To take another common instance, commuto occurs 9 times in the corpus inscrip. and always with m 3 12 times in Lucretius and always with m. Other words are more uncertain: we find in the mss. impius and inpius, immortalis and inmortalis, conliqere and colliqere, compleo and compleo 3 and 80 with other prepositions, ab, ob, sub, ad: all tending to prove that usage was in most words uncertain. Again we have eoesto, and emto, exsolvo, eaeulto expiro eaepecto cet„ s being generally omitted 3 and this agrees with Quintilian 1 7 4 who implies that it was a learned affectation of some to write exspecto in order to dis- tinguish em and specto from em and pecto; it agrees too with all other good evidence: the mss. of Virgil furnish precisely the same testimony as those of Lucretius3 yet Wagner in all such cases writes ems: surely we should keep esc where the mss. keep it, exs where they have ems: and so with supter or subter, suptilis or subtilis, ab· or ap-, ob- or op-, sub· or sup , succ- or susa, and the like: appareo occurs ten times in Lucr. and is always spelt thus by our mss. : so apparo, appello (both 1 and 3 conj.) 3 but adpetitur and always adpono, adporto or atporto, in which words the separate force of the preposition continued to be felt: in exact conform- ity with this the first volume of the corp. inser. has twenty times appareo and also apparitor, proving that in the earliest times the prepOS. had been assimilated in this common technical word: thus too in the 21 in- stances of appareo in Virgil all Ribbeck's mss. always have app. except M once, Aen. xl 605, misled by the usage of its age: comp. the sugges-
